<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="346" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1812,2017]" pageId="3" pageNumber="346">
Within 
<taxonomicName box="[235,417,1812,1837]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="346" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Phaneropterinae">Phaneropterinae</taxonomicName>
a series of tribes exist, based mainly on Brunner von Wattenwyl’s groups (
<number box="[1258,1319,1812,1836]" pageId="3" pageNumber="346" value="1878.0">1878</number>
). He used, for example, presence or absence of a coxal spine or/and the shape of the ears in the fore tibia as important diagnostic characters. 
<bibRefCitation box="[406,612,1884,1909]" pageId="3" pageNumber="346" refString="Ragge, D. R. (1960) The Acrometopae of the Ethiopian Region: a revision, with notes on the sexual dimorphism shown by the group (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae). Bulletin of the British Museum (Natural History), Entomology Series, 8, 269 - 333." type="journal article">
Ragge (e.g. 
<number box="[546,604,1884,1909]" pageId="3" pageNumber="346" value="1960.0">1960</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
and Gorochov (e.g. 
<bibRefCitation author="Gorochov" box="[853,1135,1884,1909]" pageId="3" pageNumber="346" refString="Gorochov, A. V. &amp; Kang Le (2002) Review of the Chinese species of Ducetiini (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae: Phaneropterinae). Insect Systematics and Evolution, 33, 337 - 360. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1163 / 187631202 x 00190" type="journal article" year="2002">
Gorochov &amp; Kang 
<number box="[1077,1135,1884,1908]" pageId="3" pageNumber="346" value="2002.0">2002</number>
</bibRefCitation>
) expressed doubts several times that these groups represent natural units, but unfortunately nobody proposed better solutions at present. So we will here continue to use Brunner’s characters and his grouping because it seems to be the best (and only) way to group similarly looking genera together.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
